  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) introduced initial reporting requirements\n- Focused primarily on financial institutions' record-keeping\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed comprehensive global anti-money laundering standards\n- Created international recommendations for preventing financial crimes\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act (US)\n- 1990 EU Money Laundering Directive\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act expanded reporting and enforcement mechanisms\n\n4. Modern Approaches\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- More stringent Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency and blockchain transaction tracking\n\n5. Current Trends\n- Greater international cooperation\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Advanced technological surveillance\n- Broader scope including non-financial businesses\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n6. Recent Innovations\n- Risk-based compliance frameworks\n- Artificial intelligence in detecting suspicious transactions\n- Real-time transaction monitoring systems\n\nThe legislation continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
